english:
  title: In Praise of the Oxherd of Repose
  author: Lee Suk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The name "Oxherd of Repose" comes from an unknown source. Jungam said: "The ox is a beast that man tends. When fed, it will live out its nature; when not fed, it will simply perish. Therefore, if a man receives another's ox or sheep to tend, he must surely seek fodder and grass. If he seeks fodder and grass but cannot find it, should he return them to their owner, or should he simply stand and watch them die?"

    When my teacher Shakyamuni appeared in this world, he regarded all sentient beings as oxen. Sentient beings, ruled by ignorance, wander through the six paths like wild horses and oxen in rut. My teacher, employing countless expedient means, trained them toward right understanding, so that they became full and prosperous, and lived their lives without affliction. By this reckoning, my teacher was the oxherd, and sentient beings were the oxen.

    Sentient beings possess varying degrees of feeling and knowledge, and their spiritual stations are shallow or deep. Thus the ox's coloring distinguishes them: some are purely evil, some purely good. Just as some oxen are entirely black, some entirely white, some lean toward good, some toward evil—some oxen are half white and half black. Sentient beings come in four types, and my teacher tends them with ten powers. Though oxen lack understanding, they cannot help but follow their herder. Though sentient beings lack understanding, they cannot help but follow my teacher. This painting illuminates the five turbidities, and this is why I have taken it as my name. I beg you to compose an eulogy for me, that I might observe it morning and evening to warn myself.

    I said: "I have not heard such words before, yet the principle is clear and the metaphor most apt. When the sages of China succeeded Heaven and established the Way, the Minister of Education and the Master of Music taught people the virtue of harmony, correcting the partiality of their nature—radiant as sun and stars. Yet when the world changed and customs shifted, extravagance and falsehood arose, pride and excess flourished. Why? Because no sage arose to continue the work. Shakyamuni's appearance too has been rare. Can we blame the ox for not being tamed by its herder?"

    Jungam is a man of Japan. Taking the name "Oxherd of Repose" means he is a leisured wanderer who practices no learning and does nothing. I greatly admire him, I deeply revere him. Thus I have composed this eulogy:

    Who is this man?
    In straw cape and woven hat, he tends the oxen,
    waving his arm to guide them.
    The oxen's ears quiver with vigor.
    Once trained, they ascend
    to meadows rich and level,
    where the peace of wind and moonlight prevails—
    like the brief flute-song of a child.
  footnotes:
    - 'Six paths (육도): In Buddhist cosmology, the six realms of rebirth—gods, demigods, humans, animals, hungry ghosts, and hell-beings—through which unenlightened beings wander.'
    - 'Ten powers: The Buddha''s ten distinctive powers of knowledge and perception, part of traditional Buddhist doctrine.'
    - 'Five turbidities (오탁): In Buddhism, five forms of degradation that characterize our age—turbidity of time, views, afflictions, sentient beings, and lifespan.'
